fields.detail:
1. Statement:
 <br>
 Let $ P $ be a regular transition matrix with states $\{0, 1,\ldots,N\}  $. Then, for all states $ i $ and $ j $, as $ n\rightarrow \infty  $,
$$ P_{ij}^{(n)} \rightarrow \pi_j >0 ~~~~and,~as~a~result, ~~P(X_n=j)\rightarrow \pi_j >0$$
where $ (\pi_0,\pi_1,\ldots,\pi_N) $ is the unique solution to
\begin{equation}
\left\{
\begin{array}{c}
\pi_j = \sum_{k=0}^N \pi_k P_{kj},\\
\sum_{i=0}^N \pi_i = 1.  \\
\end{array}
\right.
\end{equation}
2. Remark:  
<br>
 The proof for the existence of the limit is technical and beyond the pursuit of this course.

1. Statement:
<br>
 From the statement in the long run behavior, we know how to compute $ \pi_j $:
 \begin{equation}
 \left\{
 \begin{array}{c}
 \pi_j = \sum_{k=0}^N \pi_k P_{kj},\\
 \sum_{i=0}^N \pi_i = 1.  \\
 \end{array}
 \right.
 \end{equation}
 The first equation above is equivalent to $ \pi = \pi P $, where $\pi= (\pi_0,\pi_1,\ldots,\pi_N) $ and $ P $ is transition probability matrix.
 <br>
2. Remark:  
<br>
It appears to be odd that there are N + 2 equations to solve for N + 1 variables. See more details in DIY.

fields.problem:
( A Fecundity Model) 
The life span of  women is divided into
five-year periods. In each period, a woman assumes
one of the following six states:
$E_0$: prepuberty; $E_1$: single; $E_2$: married;
$E_3$: divorced; $E_4$: widowed; $E_5$: out-of-population.
Assume the transit process is a {MC}  with transition matrix
\begin{eqnarray*}
 && \quad \quad \,\,\,\, E_0 \quad E_1 \quad E_2\quad E_3\quad E_4\quad E_5\\
 {\bf P}&=& \matrix{E_0 \cr E_1 \cr E_2 \cr E_3 \cr E_4\cr E_5 }
  \pmatrix{
 \,\,\,\,\, &  0.9  &     &       &    & 0.1        \cr
 &  0.5   &  0.4  &      &    &   0.1      \cr
  &       &  0.6   & 0.2 & 0.1  &   0.1    \cr
 &    & 0.4   &  0.5  &     &     0.1     \cr
 &     & 0.4  &      &  0.5   &  0.1     \cr
  &     &     &      &     &    1
}
\end{eqnarray*}
What is the mean marriage periods of a woman in her life time?

The transition probability matrix is 
  
  $$ \qquad  \,\, \,\,\, 0\qquad 1\qquad 2  $$
  $${ P} =\matrix{ 0 \cr 1 \cr 2    }
  \pmatrix{
  	0 &  2/3  &  1/3              \cr
  	1/2	&   0  &  1/2      \cr
  	1/2	 &   1/2  &   0          \cr
  }
  $$
 Then, $ P_{00}^{(3)} $ is

fields.solutions:
$ P_{00}^{(3)} $ means with initial point 0, the probability that it still at point 0 after 3 steps.
When we are trying to know such kind probability, The easiest way is to compute $ P^{(3)} $. $ P^{(3)} = P\times P \times P$ .
$$ \qquad  \,\, \,\,\, 0\qquad 1\qquad 2  $$
$${ P^2} =\matrix{ 0 \cr 1 \cr 2    }
\pmatrix{
	1/2 &  1/6  &  1/3              \cr
	1/4	&   7/12  &  1/6      \cr
	1/4	 &   1/3  &   5/12          \cr
}
$$
$$ \qquad  \,\, \,\,\, 0\quad 1 \,\quad 2  $$
$${ P^3} =\matrix{ 0 \cr 1 \cr 2    }
\pmatrix{
	1/4 &  *  &  *              \cr
	*	&   *  &  *      \cr
	*	 &   *  &   *       \cr
}
$$
We only need the first component of $ P^3 $ which is $ P_{00}^{(3)} $ . So the right answer is c.

