P(\{ Y_{n-1} \in B_1 , Y_{n-2} \in B_2 ,...\}
|Y_{n}=j)
\end{eqnarray*}
Proving the conditional independence of the past and future given a fixed state of the present.

State i: Number of people infected<br>
Type of Interaction that more people get infected($i\to i+1$): One infected and one uninfected<br>
Probability of such kind of interaction:
$\binom{i}{1}\binom{N-i}{1}/\binom{N}{2}$<br>
Therefore,
\begin{align*}
P_{i(i+1)}=\alpha\binom{i}{1}\binom{N-i}{1}/\binom{N}{2}\\
P_{ii}=1-\alpha\binom{i}{1}\binom{N-i}{1}/\binom{N}{2}
\end{align*}
Note that 0 and 5 are two absorbing state, their diagonal entries is 1.

fields.problem:
The random variables $\xi_1,\xi_2,...$ are independent and with the common probability mass function
\[\begin{array}{ccccc}\hline
k &=&0&1&2&3\\
\text{Pr}\{\xi=k\}& =&0.1&0.3&0.2&0.4\\\hline
\end{array}
\] Set $X_0=0$, and let $X_n$=max\{$\xi_1,...,\xi_n$\} be the largest $\xi$ observed to date. Determine the transition probability matrix for the Markov chain \{$X_n$\}

fields.solutions:
(a)
\begin{align*}
\Pr\{X_0 = 0,X_1 = 0,X_2 = 0\} = P_{00} \cdot P_{00} = \left( 1 - \alpha \right)^2
\end{align*}
(b) 
\begin{align*}
 \Pr\{X_0 = 0,X_1 = 0,X_2 = 0\} + \Pr\{ X_0 = 0 ,X_1 = 1,X_2 =0\}
&= P_{00} \cdot P_{00} + P_{01} \cdot P_{10}\\
&= \left( 1 - \alpha \right)^2 + \alpha^2 = 1 - 2\alpha + 2\alpha^2 \\
&= 1 - 2\alpha(1-\alpha)
\end{align*}

fields.problem:
