fields.problem:
A two-state Markov chain has the transition probability matrix
\[\mathbf{P}=
\begin{array}{c|cc|}
&0&1\\
0&1-a&a\\
1&b&1-b
\end{array}
\]
Determine the first return probability
\begin{equation*}
f^{(n)}_{00}=\text{Pr}\{X_1\neq0,\dots,X_{n-1}\neq0,X_n=0|X_0=0\}
\end{equation*}

fields.solutions:
Note that,
\begin{align*}
\phi(s) = E(s^{\xi}) = \Sigma_{k=0}^{\infty}s^{k}p_{k} &= p_{0} + p_{1}s + p_{2}s^{2} + p_{3}s^{3} \dots\\
&= \phi(s) = 0.5s^{2} + bs + c
\end{align*}
And $\Sigma_{i=0}^{\infty} p_{i} = 1, p_{i} \geq 0$ for all $i$.
Then,  {$0.5 + b + c = 1, b\geq 0, c\geq 0$}
i.e. {$b + c = 0.5, 0\leq b \leq 0.5, 0 \leq c \leq 0.5$}

For $n \geq 1, X_{0} = 1$,
\begin{equation*}
u_{n} = \Sigma_{k=0}^{3}u_{n-1}^{k}p_{k} = 0.2 + 0.5u_{n-1} + 0.2u_{n-1}^{2} + 0.1u_{n-1}^{3}
\end{equation*}
Let $n \rightarrow \infty$, $u_{n} = 1$ or $\frac{-3+\sqrt{17}}{2}$ or $\frac{-3-\sqrt{17}}{2}$.
Then the probability of eventual extinction is $\frac{-3+\sqrt{17}}{2}$.

Note that from the matrix, state 0 can only be the initial state and cannot be reached from any state. Therefore $X_{n} \neq 0$ for any $n > 0$. In the long run, state 0 is redundant and we can discard it and the new matrix is $P'$.
Then we have, ($\pi_{1}$ $\pi_{2}$) = ($\pi_{1}$ $\pi_{2}$)$P'$, i.e. $\pi_{1} + \pi_{2} = 1$.
\begin{align*}
\pi_{1} &= 0.6\pi_{1} + 0.3\pi_{2}\\
\pi_{2} &= 0.4\pi_{1} + 0.7\pi_{2}\\
\pi_{1} &+ \pi_{2} = 1
\end{align*}
Solving the equations, {$\pi_{1} = \frac{3}{7}, \pi_{2} = \frac{4}{7}$.}
If n is very large, the approximate distribution of $X_{n}$ is, {$P(X_{n} = 1) = \frac{3}{7}, P(X_{n} = 2) = \frac{4}{7}$.}

Set $Y_{n} = (X_{n-1}, X_{n})$. Then $\{Y_{n}\}$ is a MC with state space $\{ (S,S),(S,C),(C,S),(C,C)\}$ and the transition probability matrix is displayed as in the picture.
Let 0, 1, 2 and 3 denote $(S,S),(S,C),(C,S),(C,C)$ respectively. Then,
 ($\pi_{0}$ $\pi_{1}$ $\pi_{2}$ $\pi_{3}$) = ($\pi_{0}$ $\pi_{1}$ $\pi_{2}$ $\pi_{3}$)$P$, $\pi_{0}+ \pi_{1}+\pi_{2} +\pi_{3} = 1$.
 i.e.
 \begin{align*}
 \pi_{0} &= 0.9\pi_{0} + 0.5\pi_{2}\\
\pi_{1} &= 0.1 \pi_{0} + 0.5\pi_{2}\\
\pi_{2} &= 0.5\pi_{1} + 0.2\pi_{3}\\
\pi_{3} &= 0.5\pi_{1} + 0.8\pi_{3}\\
\pi_{0}&+ \pi_{1}+\pi_{2} + \pi_{3}= 1
 \end{align*}
 Solving the equations, {$\pi_{0} = \frac{10}{19}, \pi_{1} = \pi_{2} = \frac{2}{19}, \pi_{3} = \frac{5}{19}$.}
For large $n$,
\begin{align*}
P(X_{n+1} = S, X_{n} = C, X_{n-1} = S) &= P(X_{n+1} = S | X_{n}= C, X_{n-1} = S) P(X_{n} = C, X_{n-1} = S)\\
&= P_{12} \times \pi_{1} = \frac{1}{19}
\end{align*}

We have, ($\pi_{0}$ $\pi_{1}$) = ($\pi_{0}$ $\pi_{1}$)$P$, $\pi_{0} + \pi_{1} = 1$.
i.e.
\begin{align*}
\pi_{0} &= 0.2\pi_{0} + 0.7\pi_{1}\\
\pi_{1} &= 0.8\pi_{0} + 0.3\pi_{1}\\
\pi_{0} &+ \pi_{1} = 1
\end{align*}
 Solving the equations, {$\pi_{0} = \frac{7}{15}, \pi_{1}= \frac{8}{15}, \pi_{0} \times P_{01} = \frac{7}{15} \times 0.8 = \frac{28}{75}$}
 The long run fraction of transitions from state 0 to 1 is $\frac{28}{75}$.

fields.problem:
Suppose that a production process changes state according to a Markov process whose transition probability matrix is given by
\[
\mathbf{P} = 
\begin{array}{l}
\begin{array}{lllll}
\hspace{0.075cm} &   \ \ \ 0 \ & \hspace{0.15cm} \ 1 \ \  & \hspace{0.1cm}   2 \ \ & \hspace{0.125cm}    
 3 \ \ \ \  \\
\end{array}\\
\begin{array}{c}
0\\
1\\
2\\
3\\
\end{array}
\begin{Vmatrix}
0.3    & 0.5	& 0 	& 0.2 \\ 
0.5  & 0.2   & 0.2 	& 0.1 \\ 
0.2  & 0.3 & 0.4 	& 0.1	\\ 
0.1	  & 0.2 	& 0.4 	& 0.3  \\ 
\end{Vmatrix}
\end{array}
\] <br>
(a) Suppose that states 0 and 1 are “In-Control” while states 2 and 3 are deemed “Out-of-Control.” In the long run, what fraction of time is the process Out-of-Control? <br>
(b) In the long run, what fraction of transitions are from an In-Control state to an Out-of-Control state?

fields.solutions:
(a). <br>
The long-run fraction of time that urn A contain $i$ balls is defined as $\pi_i$, expressed in the following matrix equation for $i = 0, 1, 2, 3$: 
\begin{align*}
\left[\pi_0 \ \pi_1 \ \pi_2 \ \pi_3 \ \right] = \mathbf{\pi}
&= \mathbf{\pi} \cdot \mathbf{P} = \mathbf{\pi} \cdot \begin{bmatrix}
0.3    & 0.5	& 0 	& 0.2 \\ 
0.5  & 0.2   & 0.2 	& 0.1 \\ 
0.2  & 0.3 & 0.4 	& 0.1	\\ 
0.1	  & 0.2 	& 0.4 	& 0.3  \\ 
\end{bmatrix} \\
\mathbf{\pi}^T
&= \mathbf{P}^T \cdot \mathbf{\pi}^T \\
\left(\mathbf{P}^T - \mathbf{I}_4 \right) \cdot \mathbf{\pi}^T 
&= \mathbf{0} \hspace{0.5cm} 
\end{align*}
together with $\pi_0 + \pi_1 + \pi_2 + \pi_3 = 1$ to solve the solution of $\pi$, we have:
\begin{align*}
\left[
\begin{array}{c}
\begin{array}{ccc}
& & \\
& \mathbf{P}^T - \mathbf{I}_4 & \\
& & \\
\end{array}\\
\begin{array}{cccc}
\hline
1 & 1 & 1 & 1 
\end{array}
\end{array} \right] \cdot  \mathbf{\pi}^T 
&= \left[ \begin{array}{c}
0\\ 0\\ 0\\ 0\\ 1\\
\end{array} \right]
\end{align*}

where $\mathbf{I}_4$ is the 4 by 4 identity matrix. <br> <br>
Let 
\[
\mathbf{A} =
\left[
\begin{array}{c}
\begin{array}{ccc}
& & \\
& \mathbf{P}^T - \mathbf{I}_4 & \\
& & \\
\end{array}\\
\begin{array}{cccc}
\hline
1 & 1 & 1 & 1 
\end{array}
\end{array} \right]
\ , \
\mathbf{b} = \left[ \begin{array}{c}
0\\ 0\\ 0\\ 0\\ 1\\
\end{array} \right]
\] 
By least square method, the optimal solution of $\pi$ is given as:
\begin{align*}
\therefore \ \mathbf{A} \mathbf{\pi}^T &= \mathbf{b}\\
\mathbf{\pi}^T &= \left(\mathbf{A}^T \mathbf{A} \right)^{-1} \mathbf{A}^T \mathbf{b} \
\end{align*}
Finally, we have:
\[
\pi_0 = \frac{117}{379} \ , \ \pi_1 = \frac{119}{379} \ , \ \pi_2 = \frac{81}{379} \ \text{and} \ \pi_3 = \frac{62}{379}.
\]
and the desired long run fraction is $\underline{\pi_2 + \pi_3 = 81/379 + 62/379 = 143/379 \approx 0.3773}$. <br> 
<br>
(b). <br>
 The fraction of transitions are from an In-Control state to an Out-of-Control state is:
\begin{align*}
&\lim\limits_{n \longrightarrow \infty} P(X_{n+1} = 2 \cup X_{n+1} = 3 \ | \ X_n = 0 \cup X_n = 1)\\
&= \lim\limits_{n \longrightarrow \infty} P(X_{n+1} = 2 \cup X_{n+1} = 3 )\\
&= \pi_2 + \pi_3 \\
&= 81/379 + 62/379 = \underline{143/379}
\end{align*}

