\end{array}
\end{align*}

First, we prove the statement is true.
 With the definition of age and excess life, we have
 \begin{eqnarray*}
Pr\{N(t) = k\} &=&Pr\{N(t)\geq k\}-Pr\{N(t)\geq k+1\}\\
&=& Pr\{W_k\leq t\}-Pr\{  W_{k+1}\leq t\}\\
&=& Pr\{W_k\leq t < W_{k+1}\}\\
&=& \int_{0}^{t}\int_{t-z}^{\infty} dF(\xi)dF_k(z)\\
&=&\int_{0}^{t} [1-F(t-z)]dF_k(z)
 \end{eqnarray*}
So we finish the proof of the statement. Now we assume that $$ dF_k(z) = \frac{\lambda^kz^{k-1}}{(k-1)!}e^{-\lambda z}dz ~~~ for ~z>0.$$
So we have $ F(z)=1-e^{-\lambda z} $, then
\begin{eqnarray*}
 Pr\{N(t) = k\} &=& \int_{0}^{t} e^{-\lambda t+ \lambda z}\frac{\lambda^k z^{k-1}}{(k-1)!}e^{-\lambda z} dz\\
 &=& \frac{(\lambda t)^k}{k!}e^{-\lambda t}
\end{eqnarray*}
So the correct answer is c.

Since $ \gamma_t = W_{N(t)+1} -t $, with the identity above, we have:
 \begin{eqnarray*}
E[\gamma_t]&=& E[W_{N(t)+1} -t]\\
&=& E[W_{N(t)+1}] -t\\
&=& E[X_1](1+M(t)) -t
 \end{eqnarray*}

With the result of erercise 7.3.3. We have $  W_{N(t)+1}$ and $ N(t) $ are independent. So we just need to compute $ E[W_{N(t)+1}] $ and $ E[\frac{1}{N(t)+1}] $ separately.
 $$ E[W_{N(t)+1}] = E[X_1](E[N(t)+1]) = \frac{1}{\lambda}(\lambda t+1)$$and
 \begin{eqnarray*}
 E[\frac{1}{N(t)+1}] &=& \sum_{k=0}^{\infty} \frac{(\lambda t)^k e^{-\lambda t}}{k!}\frac{1}{k+1}\\
 &=& (\sum_{k=0}^{\infty} \frac{(\lambda t)^k e^{-\lambda t}}{k!}-e^{-\lambda t})\frac{1}{\lambda t}\\
 &=& (1-e^{-\lambda t})\frac{1}{\lambda t}
 \end{eqnarray*}
So $$ E[\frac{W_{N(t)+1}}{N(t)+1}] = E[W_{N(t)+1}]E[\frac{1}{N(t)+1}] = \frac{1}{\lambda}[1-e^{-\lambda t}](1+\frac{1}{\lambda t})$$
So the right answer is (d).

With the defintion of the poisson process, we have:
 \begin{eqnarray*}
 E[W_{N(t)+1}] &=& \int_{0}^{\infty} P(W_{N(t)+1}>x)dx\\
 &=& \int_{0}^{\infty} P(N(x) < N(t)+1)dx\\
 &=& t+\int_{t}^{\infty}P(N(t-x) < 1)dx\\
 &=& t+\int_{t}^{\infty}e^{-\lambda (x-t)}dx\\
 &=& t+\frac{1}{\lambda}
 \end{eqnarray*}
So the right answer is (b).

fields.problem:
This problem is designed to aid in the understanding of length-biased sampling. Let $ X $ be a uniformly distributed random variable on $ [0,1] $. Then, $ X $ divides $ [0,1] $ into the subintervals $ [0,X] $ and $ (X,1] $. By symmetry, each subinterval has mean length $ \frac{1}{2} $. Now pick one of these subintervals at random in the following way: Let $  Y $ be independent of $ X $ and uniformly distributed on $ [0,1] $, and pick the subinterval $ [0,X] $ or $ (X,1] $ that $ Y $ falls in. Let $ L $ be the length of the subinterval so chosen. Formally,
\[  L= \left\{
\begin{array}{ll}
X, & Y\leq X \\
1-X, & Y > X \\

\end{array} 
\right. \]
Determine the mean of $ L $.

fields.solutions:
We need to realize that $ D(t) = \min\{\delta_t, \gamma_t\} $. So when $ 0 < x < t $, the density funtion of $ D(t) $ is:
<br>
 \begin{eqnarray*}
P(D(t)\leq x)&=& 1-P(D(t) >  x)\\
&=& 1-P(\min\{\delta_t, \gamma_t\}> x)\\
&=& 1-P(\delta_t>x, \gamma_t> x)\\
&=& 1-e^{-2\lambda x}
 \end{eqnarray*}
After knowing the density function, the expectation is easy to compute that  $ E[D(t)] = 1-\frac{1}{2\lambda}e^{-2\lambda t} $.
 

So the right answer is (a).

